g forces in the development of multiculturalism policy. In doing so, she challenges the widely held notion that multiculturalism was a product of the 1960s formulated and promoted by “mainstream” Canadians and places the emergence of Canadian multiculturalism within a transnational context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivic leadersxPolitical activityxHistoryx20th centuryxCanada. 0aCivic leadersxPolitical activityzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aElite (Social sciences)xHistoryx20th centuryxCanada. 0aElite (Social sciences)zCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aEthnicityxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxCanada. 0aEthnicityxPolitical aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aJapanese CanadiansxEthnic identityxHistoryx20th century. 0aMulticulturalismxHistoryx20th centuryxCanada. 0aMulticulturalismzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aScottish CanadiansxEthnic identityxHistoryx20th century. 0aUkrainian CanadiansxEthnic identityxHistoryx20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh  amulticulturalism, policy, Canada, history, Japanese, Ukrainian, Scottish.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012z978311127413308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012z978311127716540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755427840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887554278423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887554278/original  a978-3-11-127413-3  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-127716-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012b2012  aGBV-deGruyter-alles